sm, and political corruption in the United States over battles against foreign foes. Its adherents held the domestic and foreign policy of the United States to its own democratic ideals and maintained that promoting democracy universally constituted the ultimate form of self-defense. Perhaps most important, the cosmopolitan patriots regarded critical engagement with one's country as the essence of patriotism, thereby justifying scrutiny of American militarism in wartime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDemocracyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIntellectualszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, American. 0aPatriotismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical activistszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anational identity, civic responsibility, diversity, social justice, patriotism, nonfiction, history, politics, liberalism, web du bois, eugene v debs, jane addams, john dewey, william james, greed, individualism, excess, economics, laissez-faire, militarism, war, corruption, racism, sexism, expansion, liberty, freedom, independence, enemy, domestic policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226315850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226315850/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles